in my case, mine is triggered so easily- if I sense even the tiniest bit of distance, I interpret it as them leaving me. while that's smthing I'm working on and part of the whole bpd mess, it all becomes this thinking of "why couldn't I fix it? what made it so easy to leave me?"

I think a lot of abandonment issues (if not mine at least) all come from a feeling a rage that you could not control the situations that influenced the decision or event. we're upset that we didnt get a say or another chance to feel "worthy" for them to stay

the really funny thing about abandonment issues, especially in the case of bpd but this applies to everyone who struggles with it too, is that it doesn't matter HOW they left. If it was in purpose or not, that feeling of knowing you're ALONE is usually what hits us the most

I said once in my therapy session:

"I can't let anyone know how much I need. Because it's too much. I can't put them in that position because I'm always too much. What I need is more than anyone can ever fairly handle"

Interesting, innit?

Then my immediate retort to that thought was "What? No. You can't let people see you like that. You've never done that before and it's selfish. It's selfish. Others before you, always."

Which really kind of stunned me for a moment bc the LENGTHS my brain will go to deny my NEEDS

I was sitting here thinking "It would be so nice for someone to take care of me. I don't know what that really feels like at all."

And that's true. I see how friends, family, romantic partners etc spoil those they love not momentarily but day by day, taking the weight off slowly

I always feel selfish. Everyday, I dig into myself more and more and more if I'm not doing something for everyone. It's just another form of validation, right?

Though, I digress. What I wanted to say is just how fucking absurd my thoughts can be

When all I've been, since day 1, is always somebody FOR someone else. no matter who it is, I become the version of myself that would best serve THEM, help THEM, push THEM. My mom instilled this thinking into me even if she didnt realise at the moment

I've cared for everyone around me. It's something I enjoy. It's something I'm *good at* It makes me feel like I carry enough worth to be alive. Though, that's not fair for me, right? I've dedicated my entire life pretending to be proud, individualistic and certain

well. my mom is going through a manic episode. I'm trying to make her laugh, be reasonable, keep her focused etc. it's nothing I'm new to. I haven't seen her like this in years and well I am ALWAYS going to help her, it's just very hard to not be triggered to my childhood.
I also started reading some of my dream journals from YEARS ago and guys.......I think I DO have prophetic dreams as it would seem. I was so certain it just skipped me in my family lol
Also started writing again so thanks Mercury in Pisces (•̀ω•́)✧

I'm unsure of why I shared all of this.

Point is that I'm trying to trust myself. I'm trying to become better. I'm trying to not feel so weighed down, a similar feeling I've carried for my whole life. It's hard. I hate it. But I have to It's my duty to those I love to be brave.

So, as I was near slipping, this week came. And I was alone for days on end. I was AWARE, uncomfortably so. Everything I avoided jumped at me. Though something changed, this time I decided I had to face it. I had to face the demon of myself if you will

To be honest, I only hit the surface. I used to have this thought that if I cried, I would never know when to start. I shared this same sentiment with addressing my trauma. Even my old therapist commented on how it took me 3 years to actually feel vulnerable around her

I was very close to falling back into that place as of last week. You see, I don't talk about my problems with anyone, especially myself. I put up this facade that I am deeply explorative of my inner world, that I know myself more than I should at my age

I will do anything not to be in my own head. It destroyed me when I was 6. It destroyed me when I was 13. It destroyed me at 16. If I was ever with myself too long, it would unravel. All my hard work. All my ways to control my pain

Now, I hardly remember such dreams much less have such intense one's like this but I think it ties into what I've been going through lately

I don't trust myself because I don't trust my mind. I occupy myself with people, with food, with sex, with knowledge, with music and laughs

so I looked down. I said (more or less lol):

"It's not that I can't be honest with you guys. It's because I don't trust you. I don't trust you won't see how much a monster I am. I don't trust...myself. I don't trust myself."

That last line has been having a field day in my head

Though this time it was a prepared speech. I was speaking but I didnt really hear anything. When I finished, nobody clapped. Somebody said "We know you're lying. Why are you so scared? Tell the truth" and I remember feeling this total SHAME

so I realised something over the course of this week
